<HL>
   SEC Officer Suspends Blinder Robinson
   For 45 Days, Bars It From Underwriting
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18
</SO>
<CO>
   ENTI
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A Securities and Exchange Commission hearing
officer suspended Blinder, Robinson &amp; Co., once the nation's
largest penny-stock underwriting firm, for 45 days and barred
the firm from underwriting any securities offerings for two
years.
   Administrative law judge Brenda Murray also barred Meyer
Blinder, founder and president of the Denver-based firm, from
associating with any brokerage firm, with the proviso that he
can seek reinstatement as a registered broker after two
years. The unusually harsh sanctions stem from a 1980 casino
stock-underwriting in which the firm and Mr. Blinder were
charged with fraud and manipulative practices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In issuing her decision Friday, Ms. Murray said that the
evidence in the long-running case "indicates a high
probability that Mr. Blinder cannot ever operate in the
securities industry in compliance with the law."
   The decision becomes final within 15 days unless the firm
and Mr. Blinder ask the five-member SEC to review it. Both
were expected to file such petitions.
   Attorneys for Mr. Blinder and Blinder Robinson declined to
comment Friday afternoon.
   Under the 45-day suspension, Blinder Robinson will still
be able to make unsolicited trades for customers, complete
transactions outstanding, and make deliveries and transfers
of securities.
   Ms. Murray rejected the SEC's request for a permanent bar
against Mr. Blinder, opting instead for two years which, she
said, "will give Mr. Blinder an opportunity for
rehabilitation."
   The administrative case has been fiercely fought for
years. In 1985, another SEC hearing officer ruled that
Blinder Robinson and Mr. Blinder had violated securities laws
by, among other things, failing to disclose the firm's
purchase of American Leisure Corp. securities to close out a
$25 million underwriting for the Atlantic City company. In
1986, the commission imposed the same sanctions as Ms. Murray
did Friday. Attorneys for Mr. Blinder and the firm appealed
the sanctions to the federal appeals court here in 1987,
arguing that the SEC deals more harshly with newer brokerage
firms than "old-line houses."
   In January 1988, a three-judge appellate panel remanded
the case to the SEC for further hearing, saying the hearing
officer should have allowed the introduction of certain
evidence about Mr. Blinder's relationship with his legal
advisers on the casino-stock offering.
   Mr. Blinder had consulted with securities lawyers before
he decided against disclosing in the American Leisure
prospectus that Blinder Robinson was buying the last unsold
securities in the "all or none" offering. In such an
underwriting, if all of the securities aren't sold by a
specified date, the investors must be reimbursed.
   In her decision, Ms. Murray said that Mr. Blinder had
rejected the lawyers advice to disclose the American Leisure
purchases "because it would have damaged Blinder Robinson's
business reputation," indicating an inability to complete a
deal. "Taken as whole," she added, "the evidence is that Mr.
Blinder didn't rely on anyone's advice but did what he wanted
to do."
   Ms. Murray also rejected the argument that the SEC has a
double-standard of enforcement, meting out more severe
sanctions to firms, such as Blinder Robinson, that aren't
members of the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0121.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Milken May Get
   Immunity to Talk
   About Junk Bonds
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A House subcommittee is considering granting
Michael Milken immunity to testify on his junk bond network,
sources on the panel said, and a spokesman for Mr. Milken
said the financier would accept such an offer.
   The testimony, which the House Oversight and
Investigations subcommittee hopes to schedule for late this
summer, could provide the first public forum for Mr. Milken
to discuss in detail the operations of the junk bond market
he created, as well as the government's case against him. The
former head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high-yield bond
department pleaded guilty last week to six felony counts,
including conspiracy and securities fraud, and agreed to pay
$600 million in fines and restitution.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At the same time, the subcommittee hopes to question Mr.
Milken about 400 investment partnerships that involved Mr.
Milken and other Drexel employees. The panel, a part of the
Energy and Commerce Committee, held hearings two years ago
about the dealings of such partnerships in Drexel bond
issues. In recent weeks the panel has learned of an
additional 200 partnerships it didn't know of in 1988, a
staff member said.
   The subcommittee has asked Congress's investigative arm,
the General Accounting Office, to study the partnerships and
try to determine if they allowed Drexel insiders to benefit
at the expense of customers. At the hearings two years ago,
members of Congress charged that Drexel repeatedly ignored
the interests of its bond-buying clients, such as mutual
funds and insurance companies, by selling large blocks of new
issues of high-yield bonds to investment partnerships that
included about 150 Drexel officials. The partnerships often
resold the bonds at a profit within days or weeks.
   At the hearings, Drexel's chief executive officer,
Frederick Joseph, defended the operations of the
partnerships, saying that Drexel had "procedures in place" to
ensure employees didn't have an unfair advantage. Mr. Joseph
argued that the quick profits made by some of the
partnerships resulted from rapidly changing interest rates
and other market conditions. A week later, however, Drexel
stopped allowing its employees to buy parts of new debt
issues because of "public perception," Mr. Joseph said.
   The GAO hasn't begun its review of the partnerships, so it
is unclear what new information may emerge. However, a
subcommittee staff member said it appeared that Mr. Milken
participated in most of the partnerships.
   Mr. Milken refused to testify at the 1988 hearings, citing
his Fifth Amendment rights. If the subcommittee grants him
immunity, his testimony couldn't be used against him in any
legal proceeding. As part of last week's plea agreement, the
Justice Department cannot bring any further cases against Mr.
Milken relating to his work or investments while at Drexel.
But Mr. Milken is already the target of civil suits by
investors and others who claim they were defrauded.
   If the subcommittee "were to offer him immunity, then
Michael would testify," said Kenneth Lerer, a spokesman for
Mr. Milken. Mr. Lerer wouldn't comment on any of the
activities of the investment partnerships.
   The dealings of the partnerships weren't a target of the
original 98-count indictment against Mr. Milken, nor of the
Securities and Exchange Commission's civil complaint, which
was also settled last week. The government has never charged
that any of the actions of the partnerships were illegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Crunching Zeros
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   In the March 19 article entitled "Brazil's Collor Stuns
Nation With Harsh Economic Plan," you reported that a measure
of the plan to deflate the Brazilian economy will be "the
creation of the fourth new currency in as many years, the
Cruzeiro, to replace the Cruzado Novo. . . ."
   The cruzeiro will replace the cruzado, but it is not, in
fact, "new." Brazil's currency was known as the cruzeiro
prior to Feb. 28, 1986. The replacement of the cruzeiro with
the cruzado came at a time when severe inflationary and
economic pressures were mounting in Brazil. In February 1986,
inflation was at a mere 500%, compared with current inflation
of more than 1,000%. At that time, the cruzeiro was trading
at an official rate of $12,000 and at a black-market rate of
$23,000. The Central Bank of Brazil designated the new
official rate of the cruzado novo at $12. Perhaps the central
bankers were tired of punching so many zeros into their
calculators.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John P. Szuch
   Rochester, N.Y.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing:
   Kids' Advertisers Play Hide-and-Seek,
   Concealing Commercials in Every Cranny
   ----
   By Joseph Pereira
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   TOY MCD AKLM NIPNY NLN
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Television viewers, advertisers complain, often miss
commercials by flipping to another channel or by racing to
the refrigerator for a snack.
   They needn't worry with "Video Power," a syndicated show
about video games starting next fall that will blur the line
between commercials and programming. "Informercials" -- the
word used for the commercials by Alan Bohbot, the show's
producer -- will be spliced into the show so seamlessly that
kids might not know the difference.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While critics may not be pleased, "we're ecstatic about
the format," exclaims Anthony Williams, an executive at
video-game maker Acclaim Entertainment Inc., which plans to
advertise on the show. "Video Power," he notes, will keep
kids glued to the set.
   "Video Power" is but one of a variety of creative new ways
that advertisers are slipping commercial messages into TV
programs, videocassettes, movies and video games aimed at
young people.
   McDonald's Corp., for example, has produced "McTreasure
Island," a video starring Ronald McDonald and pals in a
remake of the Robert Louis Stevenson classic. PepsiCo Inc.
has its label appear in a new Magic Johnson basketball video
game made by Tradewest. MTV may feature Worlds of Wonder
Inc.'s new Jaminator electric toy guitar on its Headbanger's
Ball program.
   "It's beyond commercial," says one MTV insider, noting
that inclusion of a brand name would be a departure from
MTV's standard practice of excising product promotions.
   Meanwhile, the related art of "product placement" in
movies has reached new heights. In "Back to the Future II," a
big favorite among children, more than a dozen brands were
strategically worked into the action.
   This trend toward blurring advertising with programming is
of growing concern to critics of children's shows. "It's
shameful and deceptive," declares Michael Jacobson, executive
director for the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a
media watchdog in Washington, D.C. "Kids particularly are
vulnerable when they aren't told it's advertising. They don't
have their guard up."
   Thus far, critics haven't formally taken aim at disguised
ads, which aren't currently banned on television. They're
busy lobbying Congress to impose a limit on commercials
during kids' shows, because a previous ban of 12 minutes an
hour on weekdays and 9.5 minutes an hour on weekends was
lifted by the Reagan administration. But just as the critics
are making headway in Washington, some of the new ways of
promoting products could circumvent any time restrictions on
commercials.
   "Video Power," a half-hour show that will air weekdays
after school, will be "hosted" by a 14-year-old who goes by
the name of Johnny Arcade. Johnny will rattle off "news"
items, such as countdowns of top hits in video games.
Sandwiched in the minute-long countdowns will be 10-second or
20-second commercials, without so much as a pause between the
news and the commercial.
   The show also will include interviews with video-game
champions and celebrities, and it will feature cartoons with
characters from current video games. A few of those
characters are based on video games by Acclaim, which has
purchased 20% of the show's commercial time. Toys "R" Us Inc.
and NEC Corp. also have agreed to buy similar chunks of air
time.
   "Children change channels during commercials. For one
thing, their concentration span is shorter than that of
adults," says Mr. Williams, the Acclaim executive. "This, we
think, is a good way for both producer and advertiser to
sidestep that problem."
   Adds Mr. Bohbot, the program's creator: "Kids see an
average of 100 commercials every day, and between 30,000 to
40,000 a year. How does an advertiser's message stand out
through all of this? All we're trying to do is let the kid
walk away remembering the commercial."
   Peggy Charren, who heads the Boston-based Action for
Children's Television and is a frequent critic of commercial
programming, says she will monitor "Video Power" closely to
see that commercials are clearly identified in the TV show.
"If we don't stop it, there won't be editorial speech as such
any more," she contends.
   In McDonald's newly released "McTreasure Island" video,
Ronald McDonald and a retinue of characters open the Treasure
Island storybook and are magically transported into the tale.
Ronald uses his magic time and again to save Jim Hawkins, the
Stevenson hero, from the wiles of Long John Silver.
Eventually, the McDonald's characters stumble onto the
treasure and steer Long John Silver away from it so Hawkins's
crew can have it.
   About 250,000 copies of the videocassette have been sold
to retailers, notes Russ Kamalski, director of marketing of
Hi-Tops Video, the children's brand of Media Home
Entertainment Inc., which co-produced the video. Mr. Kamalski
adds that initial sales of the 30-minute home video, which
retails for less than $10, seem good enough for McDonald's to
attempt a similar project. McDonald's didn't return phone
calls seeking comment.
   "It's too bad Robert Louis Stevenson isn't around to sue
McDonald's," laments Ms. Charren. "Now, every time children
read that famous young readers' classic, they'll get hungry
for a Big Mac," she says. "I wonder what we're going to get
next? Ronald McDonald goes hunting for whales in `Moby
McDonald?'"
   McDonald's also figured prominently in the movie "Mac &amp;
Me" a couple of years ago, a film about the misadventures of
a mysterious alien creature (hence the name Mac) who
inadvertently lands on Earth. In addition to more than a
half-dozen references to Coke -- the cola brand carried by
McDonald's restaurants -- the movie had a six-minute
intergalactic dance scene in and outside a McDonald's
restaurant, its golden arches clearly in view. "What's really
disturbing are the commercial implications of `Mac &amp; Me,'"
wrote movie critic Richard Harrington of the Washington Post.
   Some movies resemble billboards on film with all the
brand-name products they feature. The recent release, "The
Wizard," features Nintendo Co. video games and Mattel Inc.'s
Power Glove, a video-game joystick used with Nintendo. "The
Wizard is one long Nintendo commercial," notes Mark Crespin
Miller, a communications professor at Johns Hopkins
University who's writing a book on the pervasive nature of
advertising.
   "It's almost become embarrassing," says Edward Mintz,
president of CinemaScore, a market research firm that helps
advertisers get products "placed" in films. Hollywood rakes
in about $1 million a week in product placement fees, more
than triple its take four years ago, placement executives
say.
   "Back to the Future II," starring Michael J. Fox, stuck
viewers with a shopping cart full of brand names: Toyota,
Miller, Nike, AT&amp;T, USA Today, Texaco, JVC, Black &amp; Decker,
US Mail Overnight Service, Pizza Hut and Pepsi (several
times), among others. "Pepsi was quite pleased {with the
movie}," says Mr. Mintz, who gets paid only when products
score well in viewer-recall surveys.
   A coming attraction, "U.S. Steal," a New Line Cinema Corp.
picture starring Hulk Hogan, also will display a host of
products, placed by Marvin Cohen, head of Marvin Cohen &amp;
Associates. "I'll have no trouble finding advertisers," he
says. "Hulk Hogan is a role model for kids."
   Unlike television, which is regulated by the Federal
Communications Commission, films and videos don't face
restrictions because of constitutional free-speech
protections. "There isn't a heck of a lot we can do," says
Ms. Charren, the children's-TV critic.
</TEXT>
