<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Pennsylvania's New Anti-Takeover Law
   Fuels Controversy, Faces Fight in Court
   ----
   By Vindu P. Goel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   ACK T.FCY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BUILDING MATERIALS (BLD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Pennsylvania Gov. Robert P. Casey signed the nation's
toughest anti-takeover statute on Friday, just in time to
protect Armstrong World Industries Inc. against Canada's
Belzberg family in the proxy fight at Armstrong's annual
meeting this morning.
   Within minutes of the law's enactment, two lawsuits
challenging its constitutionality were filed in U.S. District
Court in Philadelphia, promising that the controversy over
the statute's provisions may not be over for months or even
years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This law fundamentally alters the relationship between
the corporation and its shareholders," said Richard
Greenfield, an attorney for the plaintiffs in one of the
lawsuits. "Under this law, there is no way to attack
corporate decisions."
   The new law, first introduced at Armstrong's behest to
fend off a possible bid by the Belzbergs, has four major
provisions designed to dissuade a takeover.
   Most immediate to the Armstrong-Belzberg conflict, the law
would "disgorge" the profits of short-term shareholders who
sell within 18 months after a failed attempt to "control" a
company through a buy-out or proxy fight. The profits would
be turned over to the target company. The law also withholds
the voting rights of shareholders who control 20% or more of
a company's stock until "disinterested" shareholders agree to
restore their votes.
   Another provision redefines the fiduciary duty of
directors, allowing them to base decisions not only on
shareholders' interests, but also on the interests of
employees, customers, suppliers and other "stakeholders."
Under the provision, directors would also be insulated from
most lawsuits by aggrieved stakeholders. Finally, the law
guarantees labor contracts and severance pay in the event of
a takeover.
   Many states, such as Indiana, New York, Massachusetts and
Ohio, have some form of anti-takeover statute, and
Pennsylvania last adopted such protections two years ago. The
new law's backers, which include the state's business chamber
and largest labor unions, say that it will further dissuade
raiders from making runs at Pennsylvania companies and
attract even more companies to the state. Currently, only
about 4% of New York Stock Exchange firms are incorporated in
Pennsylvania, compared to nearly 50% for neighboring
Delaware.
   But critics, including the Belzbergs, institutional
investors, and the Securities and Exchange Commission, say
that the new law so seriously infringes upon the rights of
shareholders that it will drive them away from Pennsylvania.
In any case, they argue, the law is probably
unconstitutional.
   Indeed, two individual Armstrong shareholders filed a suit
against the company, its officers and state officials,
alleging that the law diminishes the value of their holdings
and deprives them of their constitutional rights. The
Belzbergs, who own 11.5% of Armstrong, filed a similar
lawsuit, seeking to block enforcement of the law,
particularly with respect to its battle today for four seats
on the board of Armstrong, a Lancaster, Pa., flooring and
building-products concern.
   The suits say the statute conflicts with federal
securities laws, unduly burdens interstate commerce in
shares, curtails free-speech rights of shareholders,
interferes with contracts and violates property rights.
   Legal scholars said the law is most vulnerable on
interstate commerce and supremacy grounds. The Supreme Court
has upheld the right of states to regulate internal corporate
affairs. "But who gets the gain on a transaction between two
non-Pennsylvania residents?" says Ronald Gilson, a Stanford
University law professor. "That is a transaction many states
would have an interest in," particularly for taxation
purposes.
   In addition, the voting restrictions appear to conflict
with the Securities and Exchange Act of 1934, which regulates
proxy contests.
   But given the Supreme Court's recent support of
control-share voting limits and merger restrictions, the
outcome of the constitutional challenges is not clear, said
Gregg Jarrell, former chief economist of the SEC and a
finance professor at the University of Rochester. "The courts
have to give the benefit of the doubt to the state," he said.
"After all, the legislation passed almost unanimously."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Genetically Made Hormone to Raise
   Cow Milk Output Is Banned in Wisconsin
   ----
   By Richard Koenig
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   MTC LLY UPJ ACY
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin signed legislation to
temporarily ban the commercial use and sale in the state of a
genetically engineered hormone that increases milk production
by dairy cows.
   The governor's action was claimed as a victory by
opponents of the hormone, who had argued that it would hurt
dairy farmers by causing a milk glut and forcing milk prices
lower.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But whether a temporary ban would delay the marketing of
the hormone for long remained unclear, since it still must
get marketing approval by the Food and Drug Administration
anyway.
   For several manufacturers -- Monsanto Co., Eli Lilly &amp;
Co., Upjohn Co. and American Cyanamid Co. -- the hormone is
the first potentially big product to emerge from agricultural
biotechnology. Some estimates of the world-wide market range
as high as $1 billion annually.
   A Monsanto spokesman said, "We'll continue battling and
are confident that in the long run the product's merits will
carry the day."
   Mr. Thompson approved a ban on the hormone, called bovine
growth hormone (BGH) or bovine somatotropin, until June 1,
1991. At the same time, he vetoed another measure that would
have extended the ban until July 1, 1991, or six months after
FDA approval, whichever came later. The FDA is expected to
approve BGH this year or next.
   Whether to ban BGH has been a hot issue in Wisconsin for
several years. Mr. Thompson, a Republican who is up for
re-election in November, had indicated his opposition to
stronger bans but hadn't publicly disclosed until Friday how
he would respond to the latest bills to pass the state
legislature.
   The governor said his action would provide "sufficient
time to allow for additional farmer and consumer education on
the use" of BGH "without compromising Wisconsin's ability to
compete" in milk markets.
   Opponents of BGH have argued that any drop in milk prices
because of its use would particularly hurt small dairy
farmers. Among the opposition have been small-farm groups and
the Foundation on Economic Trends, which is headed by the
anti-biotechnology activist Jeremy Rifkin.
   State Sen. Russ Feingold, a Democrat who sponsored
anti-BGH bills, called the product part of a "technological
treadmill" that is forcing small farmers out of business. In
addition to the economic issue, the opponents say, some
questions about the safety of BGH need more study.
   The companies that developed the hormone maintain that its
use wouldn't favor big farmers over small, and that it
wouldn't disrupt the dairy-farm economy more than have
previous innovations, like artificial insemination. Farmers
in various states have volunteered to take part in BGH
trials.
   As for safety, the companies note that FDA officials have
already said milk from BGH-treated cows is safe for human
consumption; continuing studies focus on the health effect on
dairy herds.
   BGH, a protein that is nearly identical to a growth
hormone that cows produce naturally, is manufactured by
fermentation. The gene encoding the protein is inserted into
bacteria, which then produce the protein in quantity.
Injected into cows, BGH has boosted milk production 10% to
25%.
   Opponents of BGH said the they expect the temporary ban in
Wisconsin to help their efforts in other leading dairy
states. For one thing, the Wisconsin law appears strong
enough to activate a one-year ban in Minnesota, which was
contingent on action in Wisconsin or other states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Law:
   Searches
   For Drugs
   Roil Boaters
   ----
   By Arthur S. Hayes
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   The federal government's war on drugs is snaring thousands
of innocent pleasure boaters. But often they can't do much
more than complain.
   Coast Guard and Customs Service officials say the
boardings and searches are a small price to pay in the war
against drugs. But many boaters say boarding parties often
behave like storm troopers and leave owners with whopping
repair bills that they must pay largely by themselves.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "These intrusions on the boating public are beginning to
take their toll," says Michael Sciulla, a spokesman for the
350,000-member Boat Owners Association of the U.S. "Some
innocent citizens now face thousands of dollars of damage to
their property. Others, who live on their boats, no longer
feel safe from the government in their own homes."
   Unlike homeowners and car drivers, boaters enjoy little
protection under the Fourth Amendment's search and seizure
doctrine. The Coast Guard can board and search any vessel,
whether docked or at sea, to check its compliance with safety
rules. The Customs Service has similar latitude to check for
contraband when a vessel comes from a foreign port. Both
agencies need nothing more than a reasonable suspicion -- a
commander's judgment that something is amiss -- to search for
drugs.
   The searches can last for hours. A boat may even be
detained overnight in dry dock while inspectors search it
with drug-sniffing dogs, drills, saws and crowbars.
   Holding either agency accountable for damages is tricky.
The Customs Service can be held liable for no more than
$1,000 under federal tort law. The Coast Guard's liability
isn't limited, but the agency determines what it will pay
boaters; people who are unhappy with its judgment can sue.
   Law enforcement agencies say they have little choice but
to continue the searches. "Law enforcement isn't easy, and
we're as concerned as anyone about doing the job in a
professional, unobtrusive manner," says Rear Adm. W.T.
Leland, chief of law enforcement for the Coast Guard. "The
problem is that some boaters and yachtsmen have smuggled
drugs and will continue to do so for as long as the
attraction lasts."
   Both agencies maintain that the searches pay off. The
Coast Guard seized 37,000 pounds of marijuana and 8,000
pounds of cocaine from pleasure boats last year. Customs
seized 20,972 pounds of cocaine and 58,185 pounds of
marijuana in 1989 from pleasure boats in the Gulf Coast and
Florida area.
   Both agencies also say they are trying to be less
intrusive on pleasure boaters. Coast Guard boardings of all
kinds of boats fell 29% to 50,000 in the fiscal year ended
last September from two years earlier. Customs Service
boardings of noncommercial vessels in the Atlantic Ocean near
Florida, the Gulf Coast and the Caribbean fell by one-quarter
last year to 3,710 from 1987.
   But the widespread searches have overwhelmed free-spirited
pleasure boaters, particularly those cruising the Gulf
Coast-Florida area. Those waters long have been considered a
pleasure boater's semitropical paradise, where the Coast
Guard was perceived as a lifesaver and unobtrusive safety
inspector. Contact with Customs was rare. But boat owners see
their paradise slipping away.
   Craig Klein, a University of North Florida journalism
professor, says his newly purchased secondhand sailboat was
impounded and damaged by Customs before he even sailed it. As
a hired crew was transporting it last spring to Jacksonville,
Fla., from St. Petersburg, Customs agents became suspicious
because two characters in its state registration number were
hard to read. When the agents boarded, the hired crew was
vague about who had hired them. The agents found a gun, and
the original copies of ownership documents weren't aboard as
required.
   Customs took the boat to dry dock, where inspectors
discovered recent repairs to the hull. They removed wood and
fiberglass panels and drilled holes into the boat, but found
no drugs. The agency estimated the damage to the boat at no
more than $1,000. But Customs also told Mr. Klein that it
wouldn't pay him anything because the search was reasonable
under the circumstances.
   Mr. Klein, who says his $17,000 boat sustained $4,000 of
damage, has no realistic recourse because of the $1,000 limit
on the Customs Service's liability. "I feel violated," he
says. "My government has greatly disappointed me."
   Brooks Thomas, a Customs Service lawyer, declines to
comment on the Klein case. But he says the rule of thumb is
that "Customs is not liable for damage it causes in a
detention situation."
   Elaine Dickinson, a spokeswoman for the boat owners group,
says recreational boaters tend to have more problems with
Customs than the Coast Guard because Customs personnel aren't
as familiar with boat construction. But the Coast Guard,
which had 20 claims filed against it last year by boaters,
also makes mistakes.
   In February 1989, a 46-foot-long boat owned by Robert and
Kay Weeks Jr., of Charleston, S.C., was boarded by the Coast
Guard 17 miles off the Florida coast and taken into custody
at Port Everglades. The agents used chain saws and drills to
rip into the floorings and furnishings and left
16-inch-square holes in the deck.
   The Coast Guard told the couple how much it would pay to
repair the boat. (It hasn't made the figure public.) Lt.
Cmdr. James Simpson says that as a matter of policy, the
Coast Guard feels compelled to pay for the damages it causes
to innocent boaters. "It's sort of an outgrowth of our search
and safety mission," he says. "Why should an innocent boater
bear the cost of damages when we chop up his boat?"
   But the Weeks, who say their boat sustained more than
$400,000 in damage, say the Coast Guard proposal was
inadequate. They filed suit last September in federal court
in Charleston.
   Neither agency is unresponsive to boaters' protests. When
the Boat Owners Association brought the Weekses' story and
others to the attention of a congressional subcommittee on
the Coast Guard last year, the agency changed its rules on
boarding and searching. The Coast Guard agreed that all
agents would keep their sidearms holstered when boarding a
boat and said it would develop a computerized system to
protect against repeated boardings, a subject of complaint by
some boaters.
   Also, Customs and the Coast Guard both say their personnel
will now issue summonses only when they find quantities of
drugs clearly indicating trafficking rather than personal
use. That marks the end of the so-called zero tolerance
policy, under which boats would be seized if any illegal
drugs were found, no matter how small a quantity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0098
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0098.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ryland Agrees With Analyst's Estimate
   Of $3.25 to $3.50 Per Share Net for '90
   ----
   By Anne E. Nichols
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6F
</SO>
<CO>
   RYL
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   COLUMBIA, Md. -- Ryland Group Inc. considers an analyst's
estimate of 1990 per-share earnings of $3.25 to $3.50 to be
"reasonable" despite slower housing-market conditions in some
parts of the country, Charles E. Peck, chairman and chief
executive officer, said in an interview.
   For 1989, the home builder reported earnings of $58
million, or $3.25 a share, on revenue of $1.4 billion. On
Thursday, Ryland reported a 39% increase in first-quarter
profit, to $6.5 million, or 46 cents a share, from $4.6
million, or 35 cents a share, a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Peck attributed the recent improvement to a record
number of homes delivered during the first quarter, a 12%
increase from a year earlier. Unusually warm weather during
the first quarter and strong sales in the third and fourth
quarters last year contributed to the large number of
deliverable homes.
   But the number of new homes sold by Ryland decreased 12%
from 1989's first quarter. Moreover, some industry observers
are concerned that rising mortgage interest rates will damp
demand for new homes. Lawrence J. Horan, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Research, said he thinks declining order
trends "will come home to hurt earnings." Mr. Horan predicted
that Ryland's earnings will erode in 1990 to the range of
$2.25 to $2.35 a share.
   Mr. Peck dismissed such pessimism as "very dark." He said
Ryland feels "good about first-quarter earnings at the same
time we recognize uncertainty for the rest of the year." He
also conceded that declining orders would affect earnings "if
the trend were to go on forever."
   Ryland's profit margin rose to 3.7% of sales in 1990's
first quarter, compared with 2.2% a year earlier. Mr. Peck
said the margin will be under pressure as the company moves
more aggressively into Southern markets. "We are seeing a
shift of new business toward Texas and Florida, where the
homes are small and so are the profits," he said.
   Noting that home building is a very local business, Mr.
Peck said market conditions vary widely. In some markets,
such as California, demand seems to be increasing, he said.
"Traffic at our model homes shows that lots of people are
interested in buying new homes." In Houston, for example,
"demand is exceeding supply," Mr. Peck said.
   Ryland doesn't plan any acquisitions during 1990. "Because
the market is so big, we don't need to acquire businesses,"
said Mr. Peck. "We expect growth from increased business and
an expanding market share." He said the company is already
expanding into Wilmington, Del., and from Sacramento to San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0097
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0097.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   World Markets:
   Tokyo Stock Prices Move Higher on Strength
   In Blue-Chip Electricals; London Ends Lower
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST CANDA JAPAN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Tokyo stocks finished higher in quiet trading Friday,
helped by investment trust buying of blue-chip electrical
shares, traders said.
   The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues, which lost 139.78
points Thursday, closed 160.22 points higher at 29584.80.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Volume on the first section reflected pre-holiday
sluggishness, estimated at only 480 million shares, down from
766 million shares Thursday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining issues, 503 to 395,
while 198 remained unchanged.
   The Tokyo Stock Price Index (Topix) of all issues listed
in the first section, which slipped 0.41 point Thursday,
added 5.86 points, or 0.27%, at 2205.96.
   The second section index, which gained 6.89 points
Thursday, jumped 15.23 points, or 0.43%, to close at 3530.95.
Volume in the second section was nine million shares, up from
7.2 million Thursday.
   Traders said that the most notable buying of the day came
from investment trust funds, which supported blue-chip
electrical shares toward the afternoon close.
   The substantial rally in many of these high-priced issues
boosted the Nikkei index, they said.
   But Christopher Leighton, manager of international equity
sales at Schroder Securities (Japan) Ltd., noted the advances
weren't sectorwide, as many electricals were hit by
profit-taking.
   Moreover, many observers doubted the possibility that
index-linked buying of the Nikkei 225 issues was responsible
for the afternoon rise, saying that they would expect a
broader-based upward movement if that were the case.
   Meanwhile, incentive-backed shares, particularly Osaka
Gas, were struck by a wave of selling in the afternoon. While
a company spokesman had said Thursday that its new materials,
which might be used in high-efficiency batteries, are still
in the experimental phase, the stock was heavily bought
Friday morning, only to be sold when investors' excitement
fizzled.
   "These were really clobbered down, as investors were
obviously just looking for some quick money," said one trader
at a foreign brokerage firm.
   "The market has been trading on stories rather than
fundamentals," said Kevin Haag, a trader in international
equity sales at Nomura Securities Co. "It's just a little
game for the market."
   Investors are putting off big strategic positions and are
concentrating on speculative trading, which is fine as long
as the currency and bond markets hold up, Schroder's Mr.
Leighton said.
   But the yen's weakness hasn't abated, and bond prices are
still under pressure, traders noted.
   Kyocera ended 90 yen (57 cents) higher at 7,310 yen
($45.91), while Fanuc jumped 170 to 7,140.
   Sony continued its recent strength, up 120 to 8,470. Sharp
was up 20 to 1,710, while TDK rose 40 to 6,880. Advantest
gained 50 to 5,150.
   Hirose Electric rose 200 to 6,500, and Tokyo Electric
Power was up 50 to 4,140.
   But Pioneer fell 20 to 5,960 and Fujitsu also fell 20, to
1,400.
   The top story in the market Friday afternoon concerned
talk that Middle Eastern companies are considering buying a
stake in a Japanese oil refinery. Showa Shell soared on the
rumor and closed 90 higher at 1,150.
   Investors lost their incentive to back Suzuki Motors,
which lost 79 to 931. Isuzu was also hit by profit-taking,
falling 40 to 1,100.
   Osaka Gas ended 15 lower at 635.
   Alps Electric, which reported worse-than-expected earnings
Thursday night, closed 180 lower at 2,040.
   London share prices ended a second day of sharp losses in
light dealings Friday, pressured by overhanging economic and
political gloom, markdowns on the end of the three-week
trading account and a dearth of buyers.
   "Market-makers didn't want to be stuck with any stock,"
one dealer said. "Sentiment is just as bad as it could be,"
he added.
   Additionally, a poor performance on Wall Street added to
the market's woes. Wall Street and London were hurt by the
release of U.S. first-quarter figures for the gross national
product, which showed a lower-than-expected growth rate and a
higher-than-expected inflation measure.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
finished down 27 points at 2106.6, slightly above its
intraday low of 2105 and greatly lower than its intraday high
of 2140.2, reached in the first hour of official trading.
   At the close, the narrower FT 30 share index was down 17.4
points at 1658.7. Volume was 536.7 million shares compared
with 510.9 million a day earlier, a relatively healthy number
in light of the dismal trading volume during the past month.
   In the futures market, the June FT-SE 100 index contract
finished at 2135.0, down from its close of 2156.0 Thursday.
   Banking, property and insurance stocks were hit
particularly hard by the bearish tide, as negative statements
by Midland and Barclays banks earlier in the week and a
profit warning by construction company George Wimpey Friday
were poorly received, traders said.
   Among bank shares, Barclays shed 7 pence (11 cents) to
500, Lloyds was off 2 to 250 and Midland sunk 8 to 279.
   In the property sector, MEPC dove 2 to 479, Land
Securities skidded 14 to 465 and Hammerson lost 3 to 727.
George Wimpey slipped 8 to 227 after its bearish statement.
   Composite insurers Commercial Union lost 12 to 447,
General Accident dropped 16 to #10 ($16.33) and Sun Alliance
shed a penny to 298.
   Food and drinks group Grand Metropolitan plunged 16 to 554
after Britain's Monopolies and Mergers Commission said Friday
it would investigate the pending merger between the brewing
and beer retailing operations of Grand Met and Australia's
Elders.
   Elsewhere, stock prices closed lower in Paris, Frankfurt,
Zurich, Amsterdam, Stockholm and Brussels, and higher in
Milan. South African gold stocks closed firmer.
   Share prices declined in Hong Kong, Sydney, Wellington and
Manila, and were higher in Seoul and Taipei. Singapore was
closed.
                                                                                                       

