<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Computer Associates to Unveil Strategy
   To Bring Order to Its Software Products
   ----
   By Paul B. Carroll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CA
</CO>
<IN>
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Computer Associates International Inc. will unveil today a
strategy designed to bring some order to the collection of
software products it has accumulated in its acquisition binge
in recent years.
   Customers and consultants said the announcement should
address some of the concerns that customers and investors
have developed about Computer Associates in the past year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Computer Associates, the largest independent software
company, had been growing nearly 50% annually in the past
several years and generates more than $1 billion of revenue a
year, but it stumbled badly in the summer. The acquisition of
Cullinet Software Inc. took much longer to work through than
expected. Sales stalled while customers waited to see how
Computer Associates would handle the overlap in the two
companies' product lines.
   Those problems then brought to a head existing concerns
about Computer Associates; Gartner Group Inc., a
market-research firm, says the Garden City, N.Y., company
ranks at or near the bottom of its user-satisfaction surveys.
   Investors quickly got nervous, too, and have stayed that
way. Some analysts already were saying they believed the
company was using aggressive accounting procedures during its
numerous acquisitions to make results look far better than
they were. So, at the first sign of weakness, the stock
tumbled 50%. It closed Friday at $13 a share, down 12.5
cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading, still
some 40% below its 52-week high.
   In an attempt to get some momentum going again, Computer
Associates executives said they will, in effect, promise to
cross-pollinate their numerous products. The best-known of
those are mainframe and minicomputer products that make
computer systems run more efficiently. The company also sells
data bases and packages aimed at specific markets, such as
banking.
   The Computer Associates executives said features in
products for International Business Machines Corp. hardware
will be made available on Digital Equipment Corp. machines,
and vice versa. The ability to grab data from relatively new
"relational" data bases will be provided in older systems,
known as hierarchical or navigational data bases. Software
that generates reports from a banking package may be made
available on other products.
   The strategy plays into the major concern that corporate
customers have these days: Now that they've spent millions of
dollars on all this hardware and software, how are they
supposed to get it all to talk to each other? The strategy
should also reassure customers that Computer Associates
doesn't plan a wholesale abandonment of many of the products
it has acquired.
   Still, the announcement doesn't include a timetable, and
such broad efforts usually take several years to implement.
They also almost always prove to be tougher to develop than
expected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Shearson Placed a Big Bet on Junk Bonds -- and Lost
   ----
   By Jonathan Clements and Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP SLH
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Who are some of the biggest victims of the
junk bond market's collapse?
   Nobody can say for sure, but here's one particularly
noteworthy candidate: American Express Co.'s Shearson Lehman
Hutton Holdings Inc. unit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Earlier this month, Shearson announced it was bailing out
of $480 million of junk bond holdings -- taking a $115
million writedown in the process -- and ending a
spectacularly unsuccessful foray into the high-yield junk
market by the big securities firm.
   The fiasco raises questions about management controls at
Shearson and the judgment of former chief executive officer
Peter A. Cohen, analysts say, and shows the pitfalls of
taking steep short-term market risks.
   In early 1989, just as the junk bond market was reaching
its peak, Shearson and its money management subsidary, Boston
Co., made a big bet on the junk market. Boston Co. plunked
down $290 million to buy shares in seven junk-bond mutual
funds. And Shearson bought $190 million of individual junk
bond issues through an unusual "special purpose investment
subsidiary."
   The big securities firm funded the long-term junk bonds --
which were then yielding well above 12% -- by issuing
short-term floating-rate paper with yields of less than 9%.
   As Shearson saw it, "If I can gross 12% and pay 9%, that's
a return on assets equal to four times what I'm getting on my
normal business," says James Hanbury, an analyst at Wertheim
Schroder &amp; Co. "It was a simple arbitrage play." Other
analysts called it more of a casino gamble.
   Trouble is, Shearson's timing -- both buying and selling
-- probably couldn't have been worse.
   A junk bond manager familiar with Boston Co.'s mutual-fund
purchases says that the buying largely occurred last spring
when the prices of many junk bonds were at their peak. "They
may not have hit the bottom {with their selling}," the
manager says. "But they couldn't have done much worse."
   A Shearson spokesman says all the mutual fund shares were
sold this month, in addition to part of the individual junk
bond holdings. Shearson declined further comment about the
junk holdings.
   Which funds were the beneficiaries of Boston Co.'s
largesse? A Boston Co. spokesman refuses to say but says none
of the money ended up in Shearson's own broker-sold mutual
funds.
   Boston Co. put most, if not all, the money into no-load
funds, which don't charge upfront fees and are often sold
directly to investors by telephone and mail, and not through
brokers. "I'm sure they had some in Fidelity High Income, and
maybe some in T. Rowe Price and Vanguard," says the portfolio
manager familiar with the fund purchases.
   Both Vanguard Group and T. Rowe Price Associates said
there would have been net inflows into their junk bond funds
in April, but for hefty redemptions by a single financial
institution, which they refused to identify. A Fidelity
Investments executive declined to comment.
   Shearson has tried to blame the trip-up largely on its
former chairman Mr. Cohen, who resigned under pressure
earlier this year. A Shearson spokesman notes, for instance,
that the trades took place on Mr. Cohen's watch. Shearson
declined further comment.
   But other top Shearson and American Express executives,
including current Shearson chief executive Howard L. Clark
Jr., clearly knew about the junk holdings -- or should have,
analysts say.
   "It was a failure of management," says Mr. Hanbury, the
Wertheim Schroder analyst. "The buck has been passed about,
but the ultimate responsibility of the business still was
with {Peter} Cohen."
   Mr. Cohen, who hasn't spoken to reporters since his
resignation, declined to comment.
   Boston Co.'s decision to bet $290 million of its $5
billion investment portfolio may have reflected pressures at
the firm for short-term results. And, "You can't beat junk
bonds for short-term income," says a fund manager at a
competing Boston firm.
   Shearson's $115 million charge against first-quarter
earnings were part of a massive $630 million restructuring
charge: $70 million in reserves were for the Boston Co. junk
portfolio, and $45 million went toward Shearson's special
purpose investment unit. All told for the quarter, Shearson
posted an industry-record loss of $915 million.
   Although securities firms long have used special-purpose
units to buy mortgage-backed obligations, it's very unusual
for them to buy the more risky junk bonds. And, in Shearson's
case, says Wertheim Schroder's Mr. Hanbury: "It was a major
miscalculation."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Advertising:
   GM, NBC Are Negotiating Huge 3-Year Media Package
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   GM GE IPG PG SAA CPB WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   General Motors Corp. and National Broadcasting Co. are
negotiating a massive media package in which GM would spend
well in excess of $500 million over three years at the
nation's No. 1 prime-time network.
   NBC and GM officials refused to comment. But executives
familiar with the negotiations said the package would be
substantially more than $500 million and perhaps close to $1
billion, depending on certain conditions. It would include ad
time during prime-time programming and National Football
League games, as well as time on NBC's fledgling CNBC cable
network and its Sports Channel America cable network. The
executives said that, barring last-minute complications, the
deal should be announced this week.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Other advertisers have negotiated packages with networks
before. General Electric's NBC unit and American Home
Products crafted a three-year package several years ago, for
example, while ESPN last week announced a five-year, $100
million deal with Anheuser-Busch.
   But the huge NBC-GM deal would dwarf all of them. If the
deal goes through, GM -- among the nation's largest TV
advertisers -- would spend more at NBC than at any other
network. The big auto maker most likely would continue
spending at its usual levels at ABC and CBS, but spending at
those two networks could be negatively affected in certain
cases. If GM were to cut its ad budget, for example, or if it
were to shift some of its budget away from network television
and into local or magazinead spending, those cuts would come
from ABC and CBS, not from NBC, executives close to the talks
said.
   The proposed deal would give GM tremendous power in the
network prime-time arena and allow it to dominate its
automotive competitors on the top-rated network. It would
give GM first dibs -- apparently at attractive prices -- on
the most desirable prime-time and sports programming,
according to the executives. GM would also be able to lock
out or severely restrict its competitors from some of the
hottest prime-time shows; prime-time programs allot only a
certain number of commercial spots to auto makers and GM
apparently would be able to grab up many of those slots
before its rivals had a chance.
   The executives said GM's spending commitment is flexible,
with both GM and NBC having options each year of the
contract. Although GM would be required to spend a minimum
amount over the three years, it would be protected somewhat
if NBC's ratings plummet: NBC would guarantee certain
audience sizes -- as the networks often do -- and would make
up for any shortfalls with additional commercial time, the
executives said.
   The package would involve a number of other complex
provisions designed to give both NBC and GM some flexibility.
NBC can set limits on how much of its best inventory is sold
to GM; for example, if it comes up with another hit as big as
"The Cosby Show," it wouldn't be forced to sell all of the
show's ad time to GM at below-market prices, the executives
said. GM, for its part, could be flexible in how it uses the
commercial time; rather than buying ads scattered across many
shows, it could opt to become a major sponsor of several "big
event" shows.
   The proposed deal is sure to have a substantial ripple
effect across the ad business, and could affect coming price
negotiations for the fall season. Those so-called upfront
negotiations typically begin in June. NBC clearly hopes that,
by selling such a big chunk of its ad time before
negotiations begin, it will boost prices as other advertisers
scramble to buy what's left. Meanwhile, other advertisers are
sure to rush to calculate just what sort of prices GM would
be paying as they prepare to negotiate prices themselves.
   The proposed deal would pair two market leaders. General
Motors is consistently ranked as one of the country's largest
two or three advertisers, spending in excess of $1 billion a
year across various media. Last year, according to ad
industry executives, it was the largest advertiser on
prime-time TV as well as on sports programming. Its size
makes it one of the most influential advertisers in the
country, along with fellow giants Philip Morris -- including
its Kraft General Foods -- and Procter &amp; Gamble.
   By negotiating the three-year package, GM may be reacting
to last year, when network prices soared largely because of
strong demand by car companies -- especially GM. If the deal
goes through, GM wouldn't face that sort of uncertainty. It
would be protecting itself against major price hikes like
those last year.
   GM has been negotiating the package along with its two
major ad agencies, Leo  Burnett, which handles GM's
Oldsmobile division, and Interpublic Group's Lintas agency,
which creates ads for Chevrolet, the executives said.
   NBC, meanwhile, has been on an unbroken winning streak for
five years, thanks to enduring hits like "The Cosby Show."
But the network has come under increasing pressure from ABC,
which has been developing its own hits like "Roseanne," which
toppled "The Cosby Show" from its No. 1 prime-time ranking in
the latest season. Industry executives suggested NBC may have
been willing to offer an attractive multiyear deal in order
to shore itself up for a less certain future.
   ---
   Chatting About Chores
                                                                                                       

   Procter &amp; Gamble is expected to announce today that it is
the sponsor of a new "infotainment" program on the Telemundo
network in which the big stars will be P&amp;G brands like Tide,
Crisco and Scope.
   The program, called "Hablando," is billed as a half-hour
"information, education and entertainment program for
Hispanic women." Scripts call for actors to chat about
household chores, using and mentioning by name a number of
P&amp;G products.
   "`Hablando' is a unique opportunity to address the needs
of Hispanic women in their role as care-givers," P&amp;G said in
a statement.
   Telemundo said the show will feature Hispanic actresses
playing homemakers and a Hispanic actor as a building
superintendent. It will air twice a week in an afternoon time
slot on the cable TV network.
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   BACKER SPIELVOGEL: Campbell Soup Co., Camden, N.J., named
Backer Spielvogel Bates, New York, to handle advertising for
its microwave single-serving soup business. Estimated
billings are $3 million to $4 million. Backer Spielvogel, a
Saatchi &amp; Saatchi agency, is Campbell's main agency for its
condensed-soup line.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S NEWS: George Guimaraes was named regional chairman,
Midwest, of Young &amp; Rubicam Advertising. He was previously a
group general manager at Young &amp; Rubicam's New York office.
                                                                                                       

   NEW ACCOUNT: P'nosh Beverages awarded its ad account to
Sacks &amp; Rosen. Billings haven't been determined. Sacks &amp;
Rosen, New York, will develop ads for P'nosh's new
ready-to-drink canned Iced Coffee and Iced Cappuccino
beverages.
