<HL>
   Global Airline Fares
   Rose an Average 6%
   In Year, ICAO Says
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
AIR FREIGHT (AIF)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- International passenger airline fares rose an
average 6% in the 12 months ended Sept. 30, 1989, the
International Civil Aviation Organization said.
   The Montreal-based international agency said its estimates
are for normal economy fares priced in local currencies.
Expressed in U.S. dollars, international fares rose 1%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   ICAO said that passenger fares on international routes
rose 10% within the Asia/Pacific region, 6% on North Atlantic
routes, 7% within Europe, and 9% within North America. ICAO
said the average normal economy fare for an international
route of 3,300 kilometers was $548.
   ICAO said international general cargo rates for shipments
under 45 kilograms rose an average 2% in the period. ICAO
said general cargo rates on international routes rose 6%
within the Asia/Pacific region, 1% on North Atlantic routes,
and 9% within North America. ICAO said the average cargo rate
on an international route of 3,900 kilometers was $4.64 per
kilogram for shipments under 45 kilograms.
   Separately, ICAO said it estimates that the world's
scheduled airlines as a group earned operating profit of 4.7%
of total operating revenues in 1989, compared with 6.1% of
revenues in 1988.
   ICAO said it estimates operating revenues for scheduled
airlines were $182.5 billion last year, up 10% from $166.2
billion in 1988. ICAO statistics exclude domestic airline
operations in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
