<HL>
   U.S. Is Warned
   About Federal
   Home Loan Banks
   ----
   By Christi Harlan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6F
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   Thrift regulators and Congress should be wary of further
erosions of the earnings of the Federal Home Loan Banks,
according to separate warnings from the president of the
Dallas bank and thrift analysts at Salomon Brothers Inc.
   "A further drop in the (banks') dividend yield and, in
turn, the value of (bank) stock could have horrendous
implications for the savings institutions we cover," Salomon
Brothers analysts Bruce Harting and Susan Silverstein said in
a report.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Thrifts, which own stock in the 12 regional banks equal to
at least 1% of their mortgages outstanding, count the
holdings as part of the tangible net worth they must maintain
to stave off regulatory actions. As dividend yields have
fallen, many of the thrifts have been reducing their holdings
in the Federal Home Loan Banks.
   Part of the decline in dividend yields is caused by a
ceiling imposed by the banks' regulatory board. The ceiling
is roughly one percentage point above the federal funds rate,
placing the current dividend yields between 8.2% and 8.5%.
The funds rate is what banks charge each other on overnight
loans.
   But yields are also suffering from provisions of the
federal thrift-bailout legislation that took effect in
August. Among those provisions is a requirement that the
Federal Home Loan Banks contribute $300 million annually,
regardless of earnings, to pay for the cost of failed
thrifts.
   In addition, the banks are watching their major source of
revenue -- loans, or advances, to member thrifts -- dry up as
thrifts cut borrowings in an effort to shrink to meet the
law's stringent capital standards. The decrease in borrowings
is also helping push down dividend yields.
   "As this bank shrinks, it is going to be more and more
difficult to pay reasonable dividends," said George Barclay,
president of the Federal Home Loan Bank of Dallas. For the
first time, the Dallas bank will tap a reserve fund to keep
its dividend yield at about 8.5% for the second quarter, he
said.
   Mr. Barclay said the Dallas bank has fed the reserve by
deliberately keeping dividends low during the past several
quarters to counteract the loss of revenue as borrowings by
member thrifts decline. Advances from the Federal Home Loan
Bank of Dallas fell from a peak of $27.5 billion in June 1989
to the current level of about $19 billion, Mr. Barclay said.
   Other more-profitable banks, such as the one in San
Francisco, had been paying member thrifts substantially
higher dividend yields than the Dallas bank. But that has
ended. The San Francisco bank dropped its yield from about
12% in early 1989 to the current rate of about 8.5%.
   "The real concern about this is that net worth be
preserved," said Ray Martin, chairman and chief executive
officer of Coast Savings Financial Inc., parent of Coast
Savings &amp; Loan Association of Los Angeles. Coast Savings is a
shareholder of the San Francisco Federal Home Loan Bank.
   Mr. Martin said Coast has reduced the amount of its
holdings in the San Francisco bank by about $240 million to
about $100 million. Those holdings represent about 49% of
Coast's tangible net worth, according to the Salomon Brothers
report.
   Coast isn't concerned as long as Congress and the
regulators don't do anything to erode the earnings of the
Federal Home Loan Banks further, Mr. Martin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Futures Trading in London
   And New York Is Cut Short
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Trading in London and New York futures markets
was cut short Friday because of a communications breakdown in
New York and by a bomb scare on one London exchange.
   Late Friday, a spokesman for the Commodity Exchange
Center, which directs operations of the five futures
exchanges here, said that technicians had "sidestepped an
electric short in the distribution system. We have not yet
solved the problem but we are operational at the moment."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He said the problem was expected to be corrected by the
opening of trading today. Computers were functioning
properly, but the problem was in the network that sends
information out to customers' price-quotation tickers, he
said.
   The five exchanges affected here are the Commodity
Exchange, the Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange, the New York
Cotton Exchange, the New York Mercantile Exchange and the New
York Futures Exchange. All ceased trading about 90 minutes
earlier than usual.
   On the London Futures and Options Exchange, trading had
hardly begun when it was stopped by a bomb scare. The
exchange reopened at 2:30 p.m. London time, to have a closing
call. The exchange trades coffee, sugar, cocoa and gas
(heating) oil futures.
   New York analysts and dealers said it was the first time
they can recall trading being disrupted in both New York and
London futures markets on the same day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Broad Inc. Net Rose
   22% in Second Period
   To Total $9.9 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BRO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Broad Inc. said fiscal second-quarter net
income rose 22% to $9.9 million, or 30 cents a share, as the
first profits from Broad's acquisition of Integrated
Resources Inc.'s core financial services businesses boosted
profit.
   Eli Broad, chairman and chief executive officer, said he
expects net for the year ending Sept. 30 to be in line with
analysts' estimates of $1.20 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Broad based his projection on sharply reduced overhead
expenses as a result of the company's consolidating and
computerizing its back-office operations here and a higher
level of both investment and fee income on increased assets.
They include about $4 billion of annuity reserves and assets
under management acquired from Integrated in January.
   "We're looking forward to continued revenue and profit
increases as all the things we've done in the last two years
come on line," said Mr. Broad. "We're just starting to get
the benefits."
   The back-office operations will be completely computerized
by September, he said. Broad has spent about $15 million in
the past 18 months to install laser-imaging equipment that
"eliminates over 90% of the paper we have to handle."
   The company's earnings in the period ended March 31
exceeded those of any quarter since Broad was transformed
into a financial-service concern in March 1989 through a
restructuring of the former Kaufman &amp; Broad Inc. In 1989's
second quarter, Broad had net of $8.1 million, or 25 cents a
share.
   Broad primarily sells tax-deferred, single premium
annuities. Annuity buyers pay the company a lump sum at
purchase in return for the company's repayment of principal
plus interest, usually at a much later date.
   The company's operating profit before investment losses
rose 56%, to $13.1 million from $8.4 million; investment
losses were about $5.1 million, compared with $459,000. The
year-ago quarter included a $675,000 gain on the corporate
restructuring.
   In the first half, net was $13.2 million, or 40 cents a
share, compared with a net loss of $11.2 million, or 37 cents
a share, a year earlier. The earlier result included $27
million in charges related to the restructuring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
