<HL>
   International:
   Import Contracts Signed
   By Big Japan Firms Soar
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Import contracts signed by Japan's major trading
companies in March jumped a record 53.8% from a year earlier
to 2.874 trillion yen ($18.05 billion), the Japan Foreign
Trade Council said Friday.
   Export contracts climbed 39.9% to 3.406 trillion yen,
posting the strongest year-on-year advance since March 1982.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A council official attributed the rise in export contracts
to sharp increases in plant and machinery export contracts
during March.
   A rise in fuel import contracts paced the overall advance
in the import category, with the council citing a weakening
of the oil market as a factor prompting an increase in
contracts signed.
   The council's monthly reports are based on contract
statistics provided by 18 major Japanese trading companies,
and are widely considered to be short-term indicators of
overall trade trends. The companies furnishing contract
statistics account for roughly half of Japan's general
exports and about two-thirds of imports.
   In February, export contracts rose 1.2% from the year
before, the first increase in three months. Imports edged up
0.3%, the smallest rise in four months.
   For fiscal 1989, export contracts rose 10.1% to 14.568
trillion yen, while import contracts climbed 20.4% to 17.088
trillion yen.
</TEXT>
