<HL>
   Another Large
   California Thrift
   Is Seized by U.S.
   ---
   S&amp;L Unit of Financial Corp.
   Of Santa Barbara Calls
   Step `Complete Surprise'
   ----
   By William Celis III
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   FSB BAC
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   Federal regulators seized yet another large California
thrift, Santa Barbara Savings &amp; Loan Association, just weeks
after the company's parent, Financial Corp. of Santa Barbara,
completed a recapitalization that left it nominally solvent.
   Santa Barbara Savings is one of several of California's
biggest S&amp;Ls that have failed recently, or are in danger of
failing, because of a second wave of problems brought on by
ill-fated diversification either outside the state or outside
traditional home-loan lending.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Association of Beverly Hills and
Valley Federal Savings &amp; Loan of Van Nuys, for instance,
currently are insolvent but haven't yet been seized; other
thrifts, such as Far West Savings &amp; Loan of Newport Beach, a
unit of Far West Financial Corp. and Great American Bank of
San Diego, have lost most of their tangible capital and are
struggling to survive.
   In an earlier round of problems, some of the state's
biggest thrifts, including Lincoln Savings of Irvine and
Gibraltar Savings of Beverly Hills, were taken over by
regulators.
   In contrast, about four or five other giant California
thrifts are thriving, partly because their troubled
competitors are being restricted in bidding for deposits or
loans.
   On Friday, the Financial Corp. thrift unit called its
seizure by the Office of Thrift Supervision "a complete
surprise." Just last week, the parent Financial Corp.
reported first-quarter net income of $37.7 million, or $1.71
a share, including a $36.5 million extraordinary gain from a
debt-for-equity swap.
   Philip Brinkerhoff, Financial Corp.'s chairman and chief
executive officer, called the debt swap "an incredible boon
to our capital position," adding: "We will continue to
aggressively pursue opportunities to increase capital,
including capital infusion or sale."
   But while the one-time gain eliminated a tangible-capital
deficit, it still left the thrift unit with only about
one-third of the capital required by regulators, and little
or no operating profit. The parent, which has $4.7 billion of
assets, incurred a loss of $60.3 million, or $10.01 a share,
for all of 1989.
   Moreover, the parent company recently let go its auditor,
Deloitte &amp; Touche, after the accounting firm refused to issue
an opinion concerning the 1989 financial statement due to
"material weakness in internal controls," according to a
Financial Corp. news release.
   Regulators are apt to move swiftly against an even
nominally solvent S&amp;L if they find evidence that the thrift
has insufficient controls to monitor and stanch losses. The
OTS already had prohibited Santa Barbara Savings from making
new loans, an order considered by some regulators to be
tantamount to a death sentence. Regulators were unavailable
for comment over the weekend.
   In composite trading Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange, Financial Corp. closed at 25 cents a share, off
3.125 cents.
   Separately, Resolution Trust Corp., created under the
thrift-bailout bill to manage failed institutions, said it
approved the sale of First Federal Savings &amp; Loan in
Bakersfield, Calif., for $1.5 million to Bank of America
National Trust and Savings Association, a unit of BankAmerica
Corp. Under the sale, the BankAmerica unit will assume $125.2
million in deposits and secured liabilities.
   The BankAmerica unit will acquire $78.3 million of the
failed Bakersfield institution's assets, which include $21.5
million in cash and $56.8 million in loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900430-0030
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900430-0030.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE ECONOMY APPEARS to have rebounded mildly in the first
quarter. GNP grew at a 2.1% rate, a slow but healthy pace and
nearly twice the fourth quarter's 1.1% rate. But a GNP
inflation index rose 6.5%, the sharpest gain in over eight
years. Most analysts expect the Fed to keep its credit policy
on hold, though some believe the worsening inflation could
prompt some tightening.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Machine-tool orders surged 37% in March from the month
before, aided by a large order from a Soviet auto plant. But
demand from U.S. durable goods makers remained sluggish.
   ---
   Santa Barbara S&amp;L was seized by federal regulators, the
latest big California thrift to fail. The move came just
weeks after parent Financial Corp. of Santa Barbara
recapitalized the S&amp;L, leaving it nominally solvent.
                                                                                                       

   The FDIC scuttled its planned bailout of National
Bancshares of Texas rather than bow to bondholders' demands
it sweeten a debt-swap offer.
   ---
   Bank of Credit &amp; Commerce is expected to post a big 1989
loss and unveil changes in management and ownership. The
Luxembourg-based bank recently pleaded guilty to
money-laundering charges.
   ---
   The U.S. dropped Japan from its list of unfair traders, as
expected, signaling Bush's preference for cooperation rather
than confrontation in trade issues. The U.S. also said its
top priority is successfully completing global
trade-liberalization talks.
   ---
   Stock mutual funds posted the biggest inflow of funds in
three years during March. The strong growth appears to have
continued in April, though at a slightly slower pace.
   ---
   General Motors and NBC are negotiating a huge media
package in which the auto maker would spend well over $500
million over three years at the television network.
   ---
   Major securities firms are forming a joint venture with
leading bond brokers to distribute government securities
price data 24 hours a day.
   ---
   The toughest anti-takeover law in the nation was adopted
in Pennsylvania Friday, but legal challenges may not end for
months or even years.
   ---
   Michael Milken may be granted immunity by a House
subcommittee in return for his testimony on his junk-bond
network, sources said.
   ---
   Computer Associates will unveil a strategy to bring some
order to all the software products it has gained during a
recent acquisition binge.
   ---
   Blinder Robinson was suspended for 45 days by an SEC
hearing officer and barred from underwriting any securities
for two years.
   ---
   Bank of New England reported a $46.6 million quarterly
loss despite one-time gains from selling assets. The bank is
struggling for survival.
   ---
   Wang Labs posted a $146.6 million quarterly loss,
reflecting a number of one-time charges and continued
weakness in its computer sales.
   ---
   GE's aerospace division plans to eliminate 4,200 jobs and
take other steps in response to defense cutbacks.
   ---
   Fixed-rate mortgages are nearing their highest levels in
over a year. More increases are expected, hurting an already
weak housing market.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 130,630,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2645.05, off 31.53; transportation 1128.20, off 10.85;
utilities 203.72, off 2.89.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3221.32, up
6.65.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.36, off 0.75;
spot index 135.49, off 0.79.
   Dollar: 159.30 yen, up 0.07; 1.6775 marks, off 0.0028.
</TEXT>
